com.javared.test

Class RedTestContext

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.javared.test.RedTestContext

  • public class RedTestContext
extends Object
    The context of an asynchronous test. The test context is responsible for:
    • Forking the test, allowing the flow test method to return without finishing the test, to enable waiting for async operations to finish. Each fork represents a single async operation that must be marked as finished or failed for the test to end.
    • Assertions - since assertions may be performed on callbacks of any async operation, on any thread, assertion errors will be thrown, be JUnit won't be there to catch them. For that end, the RedTestContext instance exposes all of JUnit Assert interface, so that assertions can be made from any context, and still influence test results.
    • Late scheduling - since scheduling late tasks and assertions is a common async test practice, the context instance introduces a simple utility scheduling method available at scheduleTask(long, TimeUnit, Runnable).
    • Timing assertions - allowing simple and intuitive interface to validate whether certain periods of times passed or didn't pass from various points of the execution
    Note that all the context forks must be made before the test method returns. See more at fork()

    • Method Detail

      • fork

        public RedTestContext.Fork fork()
        Forks the test, and returns the fork instance. The returned instance must be held and completed, for the test to successful complete. NOTE that all the context forks must be made before the test method returns. If, for example, we want to perform an async DB call, and when it's done, and only then, we want to perform another one. Then in such a case we want to fork the context twice at the beginning of the test method (or any other time before it returns), and NOT to perform the second fork after the first one is completed.
        Returns:
        a fork instance

      • timingValidator

        public RedTestContext.TimingValidator timingValidator()
        A RedTestContext provides a method for validating timing executions. A RedTestContext.TimingValidator may be created at a certain point at time, and later, this RedTestContext.TimingValidator instance may be used to validate certain period of time has passed or not passed since it's creation.
        Returns:
        a new instance of RedTestContext.TimingValidator

      • isTestActive

        public boolean isTestActive()
        In some cases, in a late callback of an async operation, it may be reasonable to validate whether or not the test is still active, or completed. For example, you can create a fork, and then schedule to complete it in 10ms, and schedule another callback to run in 100ms. The second callback will get executed, but the test will already be finished at this point.
        Returns:
        whether or not the test is still pending results
